http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20070603/wl_uk_afp/britainattackspolitics Brown promises tough new anti-terror measures - Yahoo! News Brown promises tough new anti-terror measures Sun Jun 3, 1:01 PM ET LONDON (AFP) - Gordon Brown said Sunday he will propose giving police increased powers in questioning terror suspects when he becomes prime minister but promised to preserve Britain&#39;s cherished civil liberties. Brown, the long-serving Chancellor of the Exchequer who succeeds on June 27, told governing Labour Party members that the public must recognise that it faces "a new security problem" requiring new anti-terror legislation. As part of nationwide debates about the party&#39;s post-Blair era, Brown told a gathering in the northern city of Newcastle he would be "tough in the security measures that are necessary to prevent terrorist incidents in this country." But Brown said he would make sure that "at no point will our British traditions of supporting and defending civil liberties be put at risk." Civil libertarians and many in Labour&#39;s traditional left have criticised government anti-terror measures, especially in the wake of the July 7, 2005 suicide bombings attacks which killed 52 London commuters. But Brown, long viewed as closer to Labour&#39;s left than Blair, said: "There has got to be independent judicial oversight. There has got to be proper parliamentary accountability. "We should give the police the power to question people so we can both prevent incidents and get to the bottom of some of these very, very strange dealings," Brown said. During a party meeting in the Scottish city of Glasgow, Brown made it clear he would revive government plans to have police hold suspects for longer periods without charge as well as question suspects after they have been charged. In front-page articles, The Sunday Times and The Observer, provided further details of the measures which they would be released this week and include plans to: -- extend the 28-day limit on detaining terror suspects without charge to 90 days; -- move towards allowing phone-tap evidence to be used in court; -- make terrorism an aggravating factor in sentencing, allowing judges to give harsher sentences; -- boost the security budget, which has already doubled to more than two billion pounds (four billion dollars, three billion euros) a year since the September 11, 2001 attacks on the United States; -- give lawmakers greater powers to scrutinise the heads of the security services in public. Blair, who has often said the terror threat to Britain is different in nature from any national threat faced before, wanted to give detectives 90 days to grill terror suspects back in 2005. However, he was forced to limit it to 28 days -- though it was still more than the original 14 days -- after MPs rejected the plan in his first defeat as prime minister in parliament&#39;s lower House of Commons. His drive was in response to police concerns about the length of time it took to gather information covering several countries, different languages and a multitude of Internet sites. On phone tapping, the security services have long resisted calls for intercepted intelligence to be used as evidence, fearing terrorists would gain an insight into their methods -- a stance Blair backs. Brown told a Labour Party meeting in Glasgow on Saturday "anti-terror methods must be more sophisticated, with earlier intervention." Brown also said that Al-Qaeda "probably" has 60 offshoots around the world in which they use sophisticated financial networks and false identities. Square survivors seek reform Putin attacks West ahead of G-8 summit Most Viewed - World suicide bomber dies in Somalia Musharraf tightens media regulations Bush heads to G8 Summit AP - 43 minutes ago Chinese energy plan reject caps on greenhouse gases CBC.ca - 1 hour, 41 minutes ago Video claims missing U.S. soldiers are dead AP minutes ago Judge in Guantanamo drops charges against Khadr CBC.ca minutes ago Mortgage Rate