http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20070603/india_nm/india301293 U.N. team to help Bangladesh tackle terrorism - Yahoo! News U.N. team to help Bangladesh tackle terrorism Sun Jun 3, 12:30 PM ET DHAKA (Reuters) - A team from the met officials at Bangladesh&#39;s foreign affairs and law ministries on Sunday to assess efforts by the army-backed interim government to tackle terrorism, especially by Islamist militants. The team will talk with officials, intelligence agencies and law enforcers and visit Chittagong port and an Islamic religious school (madrassa) during a week-long stay in Bangladesh. "The major goal of our visit is to make an assessment of the state of the current implementation by Bangladesh of Security Council resolution 1373, which was adopted after 9/11," the team&#39;s leader Sergey Karev told reporters after the meeting. "We will monitor not only legislation, but how Bangladesh cooperates with neighbours and rest of the world," said Karev, a director for assessment and technical assistance to the U.N. counter-terrorism committee. The team will also assess what technical assistance is needed, he said. Bangladesh, a moderate Muslim democracy of 140 million people, has suffered a series of bomb attacks by Islamists seeking to introduce sharia law. More than 30 people have been killed and over 150 wounded since August 2005, police say -- among them judges, lawyers and police officers. Hundreds of suspected militants from two outlawed groups, Jamaat-ul-Mujahideen and Jagrata Muslim Janata Bangladesh, have been detained under a counter-offensive launched in 2006. Six of the groups&#39; leaders were hanged in March after being tried by special courts, but security officials say their followers are regrouping under new names. One could be Zadid al-Qaeda, thought to be behind bomb blasts at railway stations in Chittagong, Dhaka and northeastern Sylhet last month. Radical leftists, mainly in its southwestern region, and armed tribal groups in the southeastern hill areas, have also committed violent acts. Foreign ministry officials said law enforcement agencies had launched sweeping operations to try and halt militant activity, while the government has strengthened rules against money laundering in a bid to disrupt the groups&#39; funding. Madrassas are often blamed for breeding militancy, but government officials said they had no clear evidence that Islamic religious schools are involved in terrorism. "After the visit, we are going to prepare a report, which will be approved by our counter-terrorism committee. Then, we will send the report to Bangladesh, with recommendations in order to work in the future," the U.N.&#39;s Karev said on Sunday. "Unfortunately, Bangladesh is the victim of terrorism and we will continue to work with Bangladesh." Square survivors seek reform Putin attacks West ahead of G-8 summit Most Viewed - World suicide bomber dies in Somalia Musharraf tightens media regulations Bush heads to G8 Summit AP - 43 minutes ago Chinese energy plan reject caps on greenhouse gases CBC.ca - 1 hour, 42 minutes ago Video claims missing U.S. soldiers are dead AP minutes ago Judge in Guantanamo drops charges against Khadr CBC.ca minutes ago Mortgage Rates Fall Again $430,000 Loan $1299/mo. Think you pay too much? No SSN required. Don't Quit Your Job Take classes online and earn your degree in one year. Refinance with Bad Credit Compare up to 4 free quotes. Serious refinance requests only. Add headlines to your personalized My Yahoo! page (About My Yahoo! and RSS) &raquo; More News Feeds Get an alert when there are new stories about: Elsewhere on the Web Missing word sees Gitmo charges dismissed European Protests as Bush Heads for G-8 Summit Diverse views on news from the right, left, and center Copyright &copy; 2007 Reuters Limited. All rights reserved. Republication or redistribution of Reuters content is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of Reuters. Reuters shall not be liable for any errors or delays 